pr_review_body:
I'm all for it.
I was confused by "where is my progress bar" the very first time I exported something.
@MasierAzulite was also asking me the same question when he used it the first time,

I was worried about introducing implicit dependencies between tests, but `T.Cleanup` will run when a subtest ends, so the scoping is fine. Given that 
```go
for _, tt := range tests {
    t.Run(tt.Name, func(t *testing.T) {
        integration.RunTest()
    }
}
```
will observe the same behavior as before, is there a significant downside to making `DestroyOnCleanup` the default behavior? This will simplify the mental model for cleanup. You would need to specify `NoParralel` manually though (on multi-stack tests).

Either way, LGTM

@mulhod thank you, this looks really good!

I just had a few minor comments. If you can fix those up we'll get this merged 🎉 

As a side note, I feel like the `overrides` argument throughout the library should accept a JSON string or a Python dictionary. That would make it much easier to use from Python directly. What do you think?

